Not the biggest fan of characters sharing cards, though I do understand that this effect is so elegant already that it's hard to iterate on it. It could be a 0 cost card, which would feel different than neutralize since this isn't a starter card and is draftable. 

Considering that silent has neutralize in their starting deck, and that collector has the much more expensive, more difficult to cast, and shorter duration weak source in YAM!, I think that sucker punch is better for collector relatively speaking, certainly in the early game. You basically always need to take some front-loaded damage cards to help with act 1 hallways and elites, and this is pretty serviceable, while also helping mitigate some significant damage against nob and lagavulin. This is especially true for collector, since fuel the fire is a skill that has no effect the turn you play it, and YAM is also a skill that is very expensive relative to the damage it deals (gremlin nob is terrifying for collector, I really prioritize getting at least 4 extra damage cards and a potion to cover for it). Sucker punch is a very reasonable damage card to be adding in the early game, and a solid upgrade as well, and the weak will even scale fairly well into the later stages of the game. It won't happen that often, but if you have lots of sources of vulnerable, a fair amount of doom, and few other weak sources, sucker punch can be a powerful roleplayer.

If you pick some of collectors other particularly good sources of weak (Dark Lord Form, sentry, inflict agony, etc.) sucker punch can quickly become a fairly bad card in your deck. The presence of some many other effective ways to apply the condition makes the utility of sucker punch less relevant in most runs, especially as you head to the late game. I would usually prioritize other damage cards over it when I can find them, that have more unique secondary effects.

The upgrade is very good, a second turn of weak is really valuable to extend doom and prolong the mitigation, which can smooth out your draws if you draw sucker punch on a turn when the enemy isn't attacking. However, you probably would rather upgrade a card that gets a +3 or more to it's damage early in the run instead. The extra turn of weak becomes more relevant later on, and you would rather focus on dealing burst damage in act 1.
